   <abstract >This work examines the debate between the luck and relational egalitarians. The former, including authors like Dworkin, Cohen, Arneson, Tan, and Lippert-Rasmussen, are said to view equality as deriving from the nullification of certain types of bad luck, such as by equalizing access to resources, opportunity sets, or experienced well-being. Such accounts are said to be distributive in character, as they are concerned chiefly with the way some good is distributed in a population. The latter, including authors like Anderson, Scheffler, Scanlon, and Schemmel, argue that equality consists not in any sort of distribution, such as an equal distribution of bad luck, but instead in the nature of the social relationships we are enmeshed in. When these are relations of equality, when objectionable status hierarchies are not present and individuals are treated with respect and dignity, equality obtains. I argue, in support of philosophers such as Kok-Chor Tan and Kasper Lippert-Rasmussen, that the two views are not as distinct or incompatible as generally characterized by either side of the debate. Instead, I suggest that a pluralist account which incorporates elements of both is the better choice for our egalitarian purposes. I argue for this conclusion in large part utilizing the work of Richard Rorty, whose pragmatism easily accommodates and encourages the sort of pluralism on offer. Such an account is especially important given recent advances in economics involving our understanding of the structure and behavior of capitalist systems and how they impact the mere distribution of goods. Such distributive concerns as raised by Thomas Piketty are difficult to account for if our philosophies must be entirely non-distributive in their character. Given the importance of incorporating these insights, it stands to reason that merely distributive concerns will be a part of any viable egalitarian philosophy. Broadly speaking, this work sets as its goal the defense of such distributive approaches to egalitarian philosophy.</abstract>
